Clever Geek Handbook

Testing cheap virtual servers

Many hosting companies have cheap virtual servers for sale, in addition, recently advertising tariffs have started to appear in large numbers with various restrictions (for example, the ability to order one such virtual server for one account), the price of which is sometimes even less than the cost of IP addresses . It became interesting to conduct a little testing and share the results with the general public. Some of the virtual servers were provided by the hosters earlier for one of my projects, on which I post the tests; in addition, a certain amount of VPS was purchased at a price not exceeding 100 rubles apiece.







It‚Äôs worth noting that the characteristics of virtual servers differ from each other, and the performance measured at a certain point in time is a very relative value, depending on the load on the node or channel, the number of clients on the node, time of day, average temperature on Mars in the rainy season and so on, so the material is more entertaining.



Debian 9 was chosen as the operating system, and for testing I use several popular programs: unixbench, dd, fio, speedtest. Using dd, two tests were done for each virtual machine: in blocks of 64K and 1M. The fio utility was run 4 times: in random read, random direct read, random write and random direct write modes.
